----------------------------------------
Compile Instructions
----------------------------------------
To compile main file, navigate to project directory: 
	cd ~/a2
Then run:
	make
This will genereate the .exe file:
	lxe

To compile test files, navigate to test directory:
	cd ~/a2/test_files
Then run:
	make
This will generate the .exe files:
	test_addr test_hex test_obj test_parser



---------------------------------------- 
Operating Instructions
----------------------------------------
To run main program:
	cd ~/a2
	./lxe test.txt	

To run test programs:
	cd ~/a2/test_files
	./test_addr 
	./test_hex 
	./test_obj 
	./test_parser

----------------------------------------
Design Decisions
----------------------------------------
Data structure decisions: we chose to use a hash table to implement our symtab and opcode table. This ensures easy lookups.

Bit Masking classes: instead of manual string manipulation for machine code, we used classes in obj_code.cpp
to set our NIXBPE bits, ensuring that our math is correct for the object code.

Literal Pool management: We implemented a safety net at the end of Pass1 to make sure that all literals would be handled and properly calculated before we reached the END.

Two Pass architecture: Pass 1 generaetes a symbol table and intermediate listing file while pass 2 is able to build off that draft listing file, 
calculate the machine code, and create the final listing file. 

We separated each part of our program into test_files and helper_functions and the main directory contains the pass1, pass2, and opcode table that we need. 
This ensures that we keep our codes neat and so we can locate certain features that we may need to fix. It ensures scalability and makes our code easier to read.


-----------------------------------------
Bugs
-----------------------------------------
No known bugs. The assembler correctly handles different addressing modes and such.

